# Agent-Ready Issue

An **agent-ready issue** is one an autonomous coding agent can pick up with zero extra context and carry all the way to a merged PR/MR: it implements with TDD, runs preflight, pushes, opens a request, and an independent reviewer re-runs everything and approves. If the issue is vague the agent guesses; if it is an epic, no single run can close it. This skill turns a request into a precise, testable, single-iteration issue.

> Run the helper scripts from the **target repo root** (they read `afk.config.json` and use `./bin/forge`).

## Golden rule

Write the issue so **success is mechanically checkable**. Every acceptance criterion must map to a test the agent can write and run. If you cannot state how you would verify it, it is not ready.

## Step 1 — Scope check (first)

- **One iteration?** Completable in a single focused run (~one PR, a handful of files). If it is a multi-part epic or tracking bucket, do NOT make it agent-ready: label it `{{EPIC_LABEL}}` and split it into discrete agent-ready children.
- **Self-contained?** All context lives in the repo or the issue. No "ask so-and-so".
- **Decided?** Real open questions make the agent guess wrong. Put them under "Open questions" and label `{{NEEDS_FEEDBACK_LABEL}}` instead of `{{READY_LABEL}}` until answered.

## Step 2 — Interview (ask only what is missing)

Ask the user one tight batch of questions for anything unspecified: **outcome** (what/why), **exact behavior** (the precise contract — signature/types, endpoint shape, or UI behavior), **examples** (2–3 concrete input→output incl. a boundary), **edge cases** (empty/zero, max, invalid, asymmetric branches — these become required tests), **placement** (which file/area, where exported), **out of scope**.

## Step 3 — Write the issue (required sections)

Use `template.md`:

- **Title** — conventional + scoped (`feat: …` / `fix: …`).
- **Summary** — 1–3 sentences: what and why.
- **Specification** — the exact contract. Unambiguous.
- **Examples** — concrete input → output, including a boundary.
- **Acceptance criteria** — a checklist of discrete, individually verifiable statements.
- **Required tests** — enumerate the specific cases the agent MUST write, including edge cases. Demand **non-vacuous** tests: a criterion like "splits asymmetrically" must be tested with an input that would FAIL if the logic were swapped, not one that passes either way. (Reviewers reject vacuous tests.)
- **Placement** — where the code and tests go.
- **Out of scope / constraints** — explicit don'ts.
- **Open questions** — if non-empty → `{{NEEDS_FEEDBACK_LABEL}}`, not `{{READY_LABEL}}`.

## Step 4 — Gates (state them in the issue footer)

Before opening the request, all of these must be green from the repo root: {{GATES}}. The request body must contain a closing keyword (`Closes #<this issue>`). An independent reviewer re-runs all of the above, so the Required tests must genuinely exercise the behavior.

## Step 5 — Label and create

- Fully specified → `{{READY_LABEL}}`.
- Open questions → `{{NEEDS_FEEDBACK_LABEL}}` (loop skips it until you answer and remove the label).
- Epic / idea / tracking → `{{EPIC_LABEL}}` / `{{IDEA_LABEL}}` (excluded from the loop).

Create as the **human** (not a bot token):
`bash .claude/skills/agent-ready-issue/create-issue.sh "<title>" <body-file>`

## Retrofitting an existing issue

Make an existing issue agent-ready without recreating it — keep its number, history, links.

1. **Read it fully, incl. comments** — `forge issue-view <N>` and the discussion often hold the real spec.
2. **Assess** against the Quality bar; identify the gaps.
3. **Interview only for the gaps** — don't re-ask what's already answered.
4. **Rewrite** into the required structure, preserving substantive intent.
5. **Update in place + label:** `bash .claude/skills/agent-ready-issue/retrofit-issue.sh <N> <body-file>`.
6. If real open questions remain, use `{{NEEDS_FEEDBACK_LABEL}}`.

**Backlog:** triage first — `bash .claude/skills/agent-ready-issue/list-candidates.sh` lists untriaged open issues. Classify each (ready / needs-feedback / epic), then retrofit **one at a time**. Quality per issue beats volume.

## Quality bar (self-check before creating)

- [ ] Completable in one iteration.
- [ ] Every acceptance criterion maps to a concrete test.
- [ ] Edge cases enumerated and required as tests.
- [ ] Tests specified to be non-vacuous (would fail under a plausible wrong implementation).
- [ ] Placement specified.
- [ ] No unresolved questions (else `{{NEEDS_FEEDBACK_LABEL}}`).
